"VEP 0026&#xa0;Written evidence submitted by The Electoral Commission (VEP 0026)&#xa0;Introduction&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe principle of equal treatment&#xa0;&#xa0;\nThe administrative impact of giving prisoners the right to vote&#xa0;&#xa0;The impact of individual electoral registration (IER)&#xa0;(a)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nE\nnsuring that prisoners are able to access personal information (such as their National Insurance Number) for the purposes of registering to vote\n.\n \n(b)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nE\nnsuring that there is an accessible exceptions process in place for those prisoners who\n cannot obtain\n this information\n.\n(c)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nT\nhe need to raise awareness about \nthe practical requirements for \nprisoners register\ning\n to vote under the new system.\n&#xa0;\nIs there any evidence to suggest that allowing prisoners to vote would have a significant impact on particular constituencies? &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat lessons can be drawn from the experience of other countries regarding prisoner voting?&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nJune 2013\n&#xa0;\n"